<p class="BubbleTitleSection">First Stop – Fort Lee, VA</p>
<p>The first leg of a recent multinational series of engagements kicked off at the Army's Sustainment Center of Excellence (SCOE) at the Combined Arms Support Command (CASCOM) located in Ft. Lee, VA.</p>
<p>The SCOE described their contributions to training, leader education and capability developments that will provide the Army with globally responsive logistics.  After exposure to CASCOM priorities and capability development efforts, a discussion on the Logistics Leader Development Strategy was facilitated by the Army's Logistics University.  The FLOs dined in the Army's second-largest dining facility located on the Ordnance Campus, which is capable of feeding over 3,500 Soldiers each meal.  Following a brief lunch the FLOs received hands-on exposure to computer enhanced, deployable machining capabilities that enable Army maintainers to reverse-engineer equipment parts and produce them in the field – a capability that helps with battle damage repair and interoperability with foreign partners.</p>
<p>The Ordnance School demonstrated their welding simulator that is used to improve welder training and reduce materiel costs.  Several FLOs attempted to simulate a weld while coached by an instructor, doing quite well for their first attempt.  The visit finished with a walk-through of the 91B Wheeled Vehicle Mechanic training bays where training is transitioning to a skill-based format to improve training effectiveness and reduce overall training time.</p>
