<p class="BubbleTitleSection">Second Leg – Fort Riley, KS</p>
<p>The second leg of the fall FLO engagement was Ft. Riley, Kansas including a visit to the Big Red 1.Here FLOs spoke with the Deputy Division Commander and the commanders and staff of 2 battalions that comprise the Army's first regionally aligned brigade.  2nd Armor Brigade Combat Team (ABCT) of the 1st Infantry Division (1 ID) was allocated to support theater security cooperation (TSC) missions in Africa beginning last March.</p>
<p>The Brigade has adapted to the challenge of being both decisive action capable for unified land operations and understanding the softer skills of culture, regional expertise and language (CREL) required for TSC.  2/1 ID provided an overview of their mission, TSC planning and execution in support of US Army Africa and AFRICOM.  2/1 ID partnered with the 162 IN BDE at Ft. Polk, the US Army Peace Keeping and Stability Operations Institute (PKSOI), Kansas State University and others to provide its soldiers with realistic and relevant CREL training.  Discussions continued with the staff through lunch as the FLOs joined them in their dining facility.</p>
<p>At the same time, 1-18 IN BN was undergoing decisive action company level training.  The FLOs were invited to and participated in the 1-18 IN BN company level situational training exercise after action review where saw how the Army is refining basic combat skills that have atrophied over the past 10 years of counter insurgency and nation-building missions.</p>
<p>The final leg of the FLO fall engagement trip highlighted one of the Army's most modern and realistic combat training centers and the nation's premier security force assistance training brigade, the 162 Infantry.  The 162nd provided a mission brief and discussed the challenges of Security Force Assistance (SFA) training and their role in the Dagger University established by 2/1 ID at Ft. Riley.</p>
<p>Continuing on to the Joint Readiness Training Center (JRTC), the FLOs were provided an overview briefing by the JRTC Operations Group.  The overview gave them insights into exercise planning and execution, as well as resources and training required by observer / controller / trainers and the opposing forces know at the JRTC as "Geronimo".</p>
<p>The following day the FLOs were permitted to observe, close up, a mission rehearsal exercise evaluation being conducted for the 101st ABN DIV.  The first of 2 training lanes the FLOs observed was reacting to a simulated sniper attack in an Afghan village and evacuating casualties with sporadic enemy activity.</p>
